<chapter xml:id="apportionment-and-division-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Apportionment and Division</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        This chapter covers advanced topics in apportionment methods and fair division procedures.
        We examine different approaches to distributing resources fairly among multiple parties.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-apportionment-methods">
    <title>Apportionment</title>
    
    <p>
        Apportionment involves distributing a fixed number of items (such as legislative seats) 
        among different groups based on some measure (such as population).
    </p>
    
    <xi:include href="./wkst-Hamilton.ptx"/>
    <xi:include href="./wkst-Jefferson.ptx"/>
  </section>
  
  <section xml:id="sec-fair-division-methods">
    <title>Fair Division</title>
    
    <p>
        Fair division deals with the problem of dividing resources among multiple parties 
        in a way that each party considers fair.
    </p>
    
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-divider-chooser">
      <title>Divider-Chooser Method</title>
      
      <p>
          The divider-chooser method is a simple fair division procedure for two parties.
      </p>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-divider-chooser">
        <title>Divider-Chooser Method</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In the <term>divider-chooser method</term>, one party (the divider) divides the resource into what they consider to be equal parts, and the other party (the chooser) selects their preferred part.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
    </subsection>
  </section>
  
